{
  "texts": [
    "Figure 9 shows the performance comparison for sample sizes of 10%, 20%, and 5%.",
    "We found that a sample size of 5% can introduce some instability during training, suggesting that using too small of a sample to measure input correlations reduces the effectivity of DBP.",
    "We also found that sample sizes of 10% and 20% showed no visible difference in performance, whilst requiring twice the amount of memory to calculate input correlations.",
    "Additionally, when attempting to train the model with a higher DBP sample size, namely 50%, we encountered out-of-memory errors, suggesting that such large sample sizes are not feasible to use for DBP to remain efficient.",
    "Based on these findings, we selected a subsample size of 10% to measure input correlations during the DBP update, maintaining performance and effectivity whilst reducing memory usage as much as possible."
  ]
}